body: Experiencing exactly the same issue, i think the above given sample is precisely similar to the model that I have.

Alright our issue was in the outputs, it appears that the output couldn't map the following back: `sequence<map<int64,float32>` likely the sequence bit was the issue although it would literally be an array of arrays in this case.

@mwil

> Alright our issue was in the outputs, it appears that the output couldn't map the following back: `sequence<map<int64,float32>` likely the sequence bit was the issue although it would literally be an array of arrays in this case.

Would you be able to give an example of this in code? I am not quite sure how to translate your answer into a solution that modifies / fixes the original posters code.

Also if you could explain how you discovered the Sequence and its nested types being the issue, I am keen to determine if the output types we are seeing are the same as yours.

> @jordantoaster well, it's a little tricky, so for right now we are not explicitly calling for that output which avoids the error.
> 
> First and foremost, we attempted to read the same output from python and then the same outputs in node.js. Python worked, node.js did not. The docs notate that it only allows for standard Tensor outputs. We mapped that back and found that this one was the only output that was somewhat non-standard (likely due to the sequence type) which is running through ZipMap.
> 
> We evaluated the model file through https://netron.app/ which had shown the different outputs and the process that the model went through. I know this is not precisely what you were asking for but hopefully it provides enough context.

Thanks, the model is am using is showing similar behaviours to what you described above. If we only call for the output label, it works, but throws the error when we also try to get the probability. The type in our case is `sequence<map<string,float32>>`.

Hopefully someone from the dev team can shed some light on how we can resolve this issue, as I imagine that almost all users want the output probabilities, it also exposes opportunities to improve error messages in the node run time.

💯 , my assumption at this point is that it has to do with [dtypes](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/dtypes/DType) and not handling more complex types than that.

We managed to find a resolution for this. Essentially it seems that ZipMap is the root cause of the problem. We changed our conversion code to the below:

```
initial_type = [('float_input', FloatTensorType((1, 8)))]
options = {id(model): {'zipmap': False}} # enables getting probabilities in Node.
onx = convert_sklearn(model, initial_types=initial_type, options=options)
```

I will leave this issue open for now, as I feel it is important that this needs to be documented **somewhere** for anybody attempting to convert from Python (SkLearn) and use in the ONNX NodeJS runtime.

Please refer to this:  https://github.com/onnx/sklearn-onnx/issues/754#issuecomment-931397744        
 
It is caused by sklearn classifier output a object with data and probability. So the type casting can not work. set up zipmap to be false can make it work. 

for example
```python
from skl2onnx import convert_sklearn
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType, Int32TensorType

initial_type = [('float_input', FloatTensorType([None, 512]))]
final_types = [('string_output', StringTensorType([None, 1]))]


options = {BernoulliNB: {'zipmap': False}} # enables getting probabilities in Node.

onx = convert_sklearn(clf, initial_types=initial_type, options=options)
with open("bernoullinb.onnx", "wb") as f:
    f.write(onx.SerializeToString())

```
